Input: Which of the following are Schelling's necessary conditions for compellence success?  Choices: a) The coercer must not unduly threaten the adversary; threat must be credible; adversary must recognise the legitimacy of coercer's demands; coercer must assure adversary that compliance will not lead to future demands; conflict must not be perceived as a zero-sum game.  b) Conveyed threat must be sufficient so as to make non-compliance unbearable; threat must be credible; adversary must be given sufficient time to comply with demand; coercer must assure adversary that compliance will not lead to future demands; conflict must not be perceived as a zero-sum game.  c) Conveyed threat must be sufficient so as to make non-compliance unbearable; threat must be credible; adversary must be given sufficient time to comply with demand; coercer must not use fear to coerce the adversary.  d) Conveyed threat must be sufficient so as to make non-compliance unbearable; threat must not include military intervention; adversary must be given sufficient time to comply with demand; coercer must assure adversary that compliance will not lead to future demands; conflict must not be perceived as a zero-sum game.  
 Output:
 First,  I need to identify the necessary conditions for compellence success as stated by Schelling.  The correct answer should include all of the following conditions: 
 1) The coercer must not unduly threaten the adversary; 
 2) Threat must be credible; 
 3) Adversary must recognize the legitimacy of coercer's demands; 
 4) Coercer must assure adversary that compliance will not lead to future demands; 
 5) Conflict must not be perceived as a zero-sum game.

 Comparing these conditions to the given choices, I can see that choice a) matches all of the necessary conditions for compellence success as stated by Schelling.
 Therefore,  the correct answer is {'sol': 'a'}
